<example>
  <title>Counter-controlled Loop: Rose printing</title>
  <program>
i = 101
while i > 0:
    print("A rose for you!", i)
    i = i - 1

print("Hope you like them")
  </program>
  <description>Print 101 roses using a while loop</description>
  <topics>
    <topic>while</topic>
    <topic>loop</topic>
  </topics>
  <explanations>
    <explain>
      <position>2-3</position>
      <description>Code block, aligned by indentation, is to be executed (again) if the condition remains true.  If the condition is false, the execution will stop and leave the structure</description>
    </explain>
    <explain>
      <position>5-5</position>
      <description>Execute always and once</description>
    </explain>
    <explain>
      <position>0-0</position>
      <description>Execute always and once</description>
    </explain>
    <explain>
      <position>0-0</position>
      <description>The counter (variable i) runs from 101 to 0, that keeps track of the number of repetitions</description>
    </explain>
    <explain>
      <position>3-3</position>
      <description>The counter is updated as the repetition is done once</description>
    </explain>
    <explain>
      <position>1-1</position>
      <description>The counter is checked if the repetition should continue or stop</description>
    </explain>
    <explain>
      <position>0-3</position>
      <description>Counted-controlled loop repeats according to a counter</description>
    </explain>
  </explanations>
